         <div type="translation">
            <p>To the gods of the underworld. Here I lie, a regretfu[l] girl, [keeping (this)] final [slumber] among the dead, having left behind the light of the sun, 
                        having lived 4 hebdomads of bitter years and 7 mournful months, which I did not fini[sh. My mother be]at (her) [chest] (as did) the [rest] of (my) 
                        family [---] no one(?) [---] </p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary"><!-- notes go here -->
            <p>A hebdomad is a group of 7 years, so "4 hebdomads of ... years" means that she lived for 28 years. This phrasing, paired with "7 mournful months, which I did not finish," standing in for a more simple "6 mournful months", 
                        makes clear the author's desire to create number symbolism with 7s.</p>
            <p>Epitaph in dactylic hexameter.</p>
            <p>Line 2: πεποθημέν[ον ἄνθος ἅπασιν | (Comparetti in Dennison); πεποθημέν[η ἠδʹ ἀγαπητή, | (Halbherr in Dennison).</p>
            <p>Line 3: ἠελίου [μεταβᾶσα | (Comparetti in Dennison); ἠελίοι[ο ἰδοῦσα, | (Halbherr in Dennison).</p>
            <p>Line 4: πικρῶ[ν ὑπὸ μόχθων, | (Comparetti in Dennison); πικρῶ[ς τέλος ἔσχον, | (Halbherr in Dennison).</p>
            <p>Line 5: ἑπτὰ δὲ κ(ύ)[κλους μοι] γοερούς (Comparetti in Dennison); ἑπτὰ δὲ [καὶ μῆνας γο]ερούς οὓς οὐκ ἐτέλε[σθην | (Halbherr in Dennison).</p>
            <p>Line 6: [Δῶκε θεός· μήτηρ δὲ μʹ] ἐκόψατο (Comparetti in Dennison).</p>
         </div>
